# CLAUDE.local.md.example — template

Copy to `CLAUDE.local.md` (gitignored) and fill in. This `.example` is
committed and must stay free of private URLs, internal names, or
anything you'd not want in the open-source release.

`CLAUDE.local.md` is loaded by Claude Code in addition to `CLAUDE.md`
when present. It's where maintainer-private context lives (the table
of bot identities the maintainer runs, links to private docs, internal
deadlines, etc.). External contributors don't need one.

## Suggested structure (keep it short — this file is loaded every turn)

- **Why this matters to us.** A few lines on how the project fits the
  broader business bet. Enough for agent judgment, not a sales deck.
- **Design trade-off defaults.** 3–5 bullets on which side to favor
  when the public docs are silent. Should be stable, not per-task.
- **Where long-form strategy lives.** One sentence saying such docs
  exist elsewhere and how to pull the latest. **Do not name private
  repos, URLs, or internal services in this `.example` file** — that
  belongs only in `CLAUDE.local.md`.
- **Internal contribution notes.** How internal humans sign commits,
  where design discussions happen, who to escalate to.
- **Bot identity table (optional).** If you run AI agents under
  dedicated bot identities, list each bot's author name, author email,
  signing key path, SSH host alias, and GitHub user. The `commit` and
  `open-pr` skills look this table up at run time — if it's absent,
  those skills fall back to whatever default git identity the machine
  has.

## Hard rules for every `CLAUDE.local.md`

- Treat contents as confidential; never copy into commits, PRs, or
  external systems.
- Never name private repos / internal services in any committed file.
- Before every commit, re-check
  [AGENTS.md — Local override files](AGENTS.md#local-override-files).
